Here's some example code for a WeChat Mini Program that displays a "Hello World" message:

1. Create an HTML file called `index.wxml`:

```
<view class="container">
  <text class="message">Hello World</text>
</view>
```

2. Create a CSS file called `index.wxss`:

```
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  height: 100vh;
}

.message {
  font-size: 30px;
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

3. Create a JavaScript file called `index.js`:

```
// This function is called when the page loads
Page({
  onLoad: function () {
    console.log('Page loaded')
  }
})
```

4. Add the files to your WeChat Mini Program project and build the app

Sure! Here is an example MATLAB script for a simple pendulum using Hamiltonian mechanics:

```matlab
% Define variables
g = 9.81;       % gravitational acceleration
L = 1;          % length of pendulum
tmax = 10;      % maximum time
theta0 = 0.1;   % initial angular displacement of pendulum
omega0 = 0;     % initial angular velocity of pendulum
tstep = 0.01;   % time step

% Define Hamiltonian
syms theta(t) omega(t)
H = 1/2 * L^2 * omega^2 - g * L * cos(theta);

% Define equations of motion
eqns = [
    diff(theta,t) == diff(H,omega),
    diff(omega,t) == -diff(H,theta)
];

% Define initial conditions
conds = [theta(0) == theta0, omega(0) == omega0];

% Solve equations of motion
vars = [theta, omega];
sol = dsolve(eqns, conds);

% Plot solution
t = 0:tstep:tmax;
thetasol = double(subs(sol.theta, 't', t));
plot(t, thetasol)
xlabel('Time (s)');
ylabel('Angular displacement (rad)');
title('Simple Pendulum');
```

In this script, we first define the variables `g`, `L`, `tmax`, `theta0`, `omega0`, and `tstep` for the gravitational acceleration, length of the pendulum, maximum time, initial angular displacement of the pendulum, initial angular velocity of the pendulum, and time step, respectively.

Next, we define the Hamiltonian of the simple pendulum as `H`, using the MATLAB symbolic toolbox. The variables `theta` and `omega` are also defined as symbolic functions of time.

Then, we define the equations of motion derived from the Hamiltonian. These equations are stored in the variable `eqns`, with the first equation representing the derivative of position (theta) with respect to time and the second equation representing the derivative of velocity (omega) with respect to time.

Finally, we solve the equations of motion using `dsolve`, which uses the initial conditions specified in `conds` to compute the general solution. We then plot the solution using `plot`, with time as the x-axis and the angular displacement as the y-axis. The resulting plot shows the motion of the simple pendulum over time.

Here's a simple example of an Unreal plugin that adds a new window to the Unreal Editor:

1. Open Visual Studio and create a new C++ project using the Unreal Engine template.
2. In the Solution Explorer, right-click on the project and select "Add->New Folder" to create a folder for your plugin files.
3. Right-click on the folder and select "Add->New C++ Class" to create a new C++ class for your plugin.
4. In the Class Wizard, select "Editor Plugin" as the Parent Class.
5. In the generated header file for your plugin class, add the following code:

```cpp
#pragma once

#include "CoreMinimal.h"
#include "Modules/ModuleManager.h"

class FMyPluginModule : public IModuleInterface
{
public:
    virtual void StartupModule() override;
    virtual void ShutdownModule() override;
};
```

6. In the generated cpp file for your plugin class, add the following code:

```cpp
#include "MyPluginModule.h"

void FMyPluginModule::StartupModule()
{
    // Your plugin's startup code here
}

void FMyPluginModule::ShutdownModule()
{
    // Your plugin's shutdown code here
}

IMPLEMENT_MODULE(FMyPluginModule, MyPlugin)
```

7. In the "Plugins" folder of your Unreal project, create a new folder with the same name as your plugin folder.
8. Create a new file called "MyPlugin.uplugin" in the folder and add the following JSON code:

```json
{
    "FileVersion": 3,
    "Version": 1,
    "FriendlyName": "My Plugin",
    "Description": "A simple plugin example",
    "Category": "My Category",
    "CreatedBy": "Your Name",
    "EnabledByDefault": true,
    "Modules": [
        {
            "Name": "MyPlugin",
            "Type": "Editor",
            "LoadingPhase": "Default"
        }
    ]
}
```

9. Build your project in Visual Studio and open the Unreal Editor.
10. In the "Plugins" menu, select "Installed" and find your plugin.
11. Click the "Enabled" checkbox to enable your plugin.
12. Your plugin's startup code will be run and a new window will be added to the Unreal Editor.

This is just a simple example, but it should give you an idea of how to create an Unreal plugin. Be sure to refer to the Unreal Engine documentation for more advanced features and concepts.

I'm an AI and cannot directly do your homework for you; however, I can provide guidance and tips to help you get started.

First, let's give an overview of the ANTLR tool. ANTLR (ANother Tool for Language Recognition) is a parser generator used to build robust language parsers. The parsers are generated by writing a grammar file using a domain-specific language (DSL) and the ANTLR tool will automatically generate code for your desired programming language (e.g., Java, Python, C#, etc.)

Now, let's break down the requirements for your MPL and start building your grammar file. Here's a brief outline:

1. Define the lexer rules for your language: keywords, variable types, operators, etc.

```
lexer grammar MPLLexer;

BEGIN: 'begin';
END: 'end';
SEMICOLON: ';';
COLON: ':';
COMMA: ',';
PLUS: '+';
MINUS: '-';
MULTIPLY: '*';
DIVIDE: '/';
LT: '<';
LTE: '<=';
GT: '>';
GTE: '>=';
INT: 'int';
FLOAT: 'float';
CHAR: 'char';
IF: 'if';
THEN: 'then';
ELSIF: 'elsif'
ELSE: 'else';
ENDIF: 'endif';
ID: [a-zA-Z] [a-zA-Z0-9]*;
WS: [ \t\n\r]+ -> skip;
```

2. Define your parser rules using the lexer rules defined above:

```
parser grammar MPLParser;

options { tokenVocab=MPLLexer; }

program: BEGIN declaration* statement* END;

declaration: type COLON variable (COMMA variable)* SEMICOLON;

type: INT | FLOAT | CHAR;

variable: ID;

statement: assignment | conditional;

assignment: ID (PLUS | MINUS | MULTIPLY | DIVIDE) expression SEMICOLON;

expression: (ID | NUMBER) (PLUS | MINUS | MULTIPLY | DIVIDE | LT | LTE | GT | GTE) (ID | NUMBER);

conditional: IF expression THEN statement (ELSIF expression THEN statement)* (ELSE statement)? ENDIF SEMICOLON;
```

This grammar is just an initial draft and is meant to help you get started. It may contain errors or need adjustments to satisfy all requirements of the My Programming Language assignment.

Once you've created your grammar, you can use ANTLR to generate parser and lexer code in your target programming language. When the code is generated, you may need to create a main file to load your demo source code (e.g., `myprog1.mpl`) and invoke the generated parser to check for syntax errors in the code.

For your report, do the following:

1. Describe the rules you designed for MPL in your own words.
2. Include details of your grammar in BNF or EBNF notation (the grammar given above)
3. Explain how you tested your grammar using various source codes written in your language.
4. Discuss any challenges or issues you encountered during the development and how you addressed them.

You are correct. There's no need to use a comma for separating multiple variable declarations in the assignment statement if your language requirement does not specify it. Instead, you can use the semicolon, which is already included in the grammar to separate statements. 

Here's the updated `declaration` rule without commas:

```antlr
declaration: type COLON variable SEMICOLON;
```

And the updated `assignment` rule:

```antlr
assignment: ID (PLUS | MINUS | MULTIPLY | DIVIDE) expression SEMICOLON;
```

Now, you can declare and assign variables as follows:

```
int: a;
float: b;
a = b * 3.14;
```

Certainly! Here's the final version for both MPLLexer and MPLParser, with the incorporated changes:

1. MPLLexer (MPLLexer.g4):

```antlr
lexer grammar MPLLexer;

BEGIN       : 'begin';
END         : 'end';
SEMICOLON   : ';';
COLON       : ':';
EQUAL       : '=';
COMMA       : ',';
PLUS        : '+';
MINUS       : '-';
MULTIPLY    : '*';
DIVIDE      : '/';
LT          : '<';
LTE         : '<=';
GT          : '>';
GTE         : '>=';
INT         : 'int';
FLOAT       : 'float';
CHAR        : 'char';
IF          : 'if';
THEN        : 'then';
ELSIF       : 'elsif';
ELSE        : 'else';
ENDIF       : 'endif';
ID          : [a-zA-Z] [a-zA-Z0-9]*;
INT_NUMBER  : [0-9]+;
FLOAT_NUMBER: [0-9]* '.' [0-9]+;
WS          : [ \t\n\r]+ -> skip;
```

2. MPLParser (MPLParser.g4):

```antlr
parser grammar MPLParser;

options { tokenVocab=MPLLexer; }

program     : BEGIN declaration* statement* END;

declaration : type COLON variable SEMICOLON;

type        : INT | FLOAT | CHAR;

variable    : ID;

statement   : assignment | conditional;

assignment  : ID EQUAL expr SEMICOLON;

expr
    : expr operator expr #binaryOperation
    | '(' expr ')'       #parenthesizedExpr
    | INT_NUMBER         #intLiteral
    | FLOAT_NUMBER       #floatLiteral
    | ID                 #variable
    ;

operator
    : PLUS | MINUS | MULTIPLY | DIVIDE | LT | LTE | GT | GTE;

conditional : IF expr THEN statement (ELSIF expr THEN statement)* (ELSE statement)? ENDIF SEMICOLON;
```

With these lexer and parser grammars, your MPL language should support the specified requirements, including assignments with arithmetic expressions and a conditional statement. Remember to regenerate the parser and lexer code using ANTLR and test your MPL language with various source codes.

Apologies for the confusion. You're right, ANTLR v3 does not support left recursion. Here's the corresponding `expr` rule for ANTLR v3 using an alternative representation for arithmetic expressions without left recursion:

```antlr
expr       : add_expr;

add_expr   : mul_expr ( (PLUS | MINUS) mul_expr )* ;

mul_expr   : atomic_expr ( (MULTIPLY | DIVIDE) atomic_expr )* ;

atomic_expr
    : ID
    | INT_NUMBER
    | FLOAT_NUMBER
    | '(' expr ')'
    ;
```

This version of the `expr` rule breaks down expressions into multiple sub-rules, starting with addition and subtraction operations (`add_expr` rule), followed by multiplication and division operations (`mul_expr` rule), and finally reaching the atomic expressions, which are numbers, variables, or parenthesized expressions.

By organizing the rules in this way, you can avoid left recursion, allowing you to use this grammar with ANTLR v3. Make sure to update both assignment and conditional rules in your MPLParser to use this new `expr` rule:

```antlr
assignment  : ID EQUAL add_expr SEMICOLON;
conditional : IF add_expr THEN statement (ELSIF add_expr THEN statement)* (ELSE statement)? ENDIF SEMICOLON;
```

Update the rest of your MPL grammar accordingly and generate the parser and lexer code using ANTLR v3. Now your MPL language should work correctly with ANTLR v3.

I am developing a conlang. For now let's call it "Alanir". I need your help, please. Let's start with a rundown of what I have so far.

Phonology:

Sounds in Alanir are organized into pairs, in which one sound is "Strong" and the other one is "weak". Strong sound is used at the start of a word, and a weak sound is used elsewhere. The glide sound "[j]" does not have a pair and is used only to link vowel sounds.

Consonants (strong :  weak : alphabet letter) :
1. /m(soft)/ - [mʲ] as in million : /m/ - [m] as in “mother” : m;
2. /ng/ - [ŋ] as in “sing” : /n/ - [n] as in “nobody” : n;
3.  /f/ - [ɸ] as in “far” : /v/ - [β] as in “vowel” : v;
4.  /k/ - [k] as in “kettle” : /kh/ - [kʰ] as in “thickhead” : k;
5.  /dj/ - [dʑ] as in “adjacent”; /t/ - [t] as in “temple” : j;
6.  /sh/ - [ʃ] as in “shoes” : /s/ - [s] as in “snake” : s ;
7.  /r(soft)/ - [r̝ʲ] as in “padre” : /g/ - [ɣ] as in “garbage” : r;
8.  /l(soft)/ - [lʲ] as in “linear” : /l/ - [l] as in “lament” : l.

Vowels (strong :  weak : alphabet letter):
1. /wa/ - [wa] or [ɣa] as in “coward” : /ah/ - [ʔa] as in “ahriman” : a;
2. /wo/ - [wo] or [ɣo] as in “war” : /oh/ - [ʔo] as in “dough” : o;
3. /wi/ - [wi:] or [ɣi:] as in “wind” : /i/ - [ʔi] as in “stop it” : i;
4. /wu/ - [wu] or [ɣu] as in “wuhan” : /u/ - [ʔu] as in baffled exclamation sound : u;

Glide: /'/ - [j] - glide as in “toyota” : '.

Tone: No tone phonemes present in this language.

Diacritics (auxillary symbols):
Weak stress  - "-" before the stressed vowel letter, exapmles: kar-il, ra'-ak;
Strong stress -  "_" before the stressed vowel, examples: _akr-il.

***

Morphology:

All basic words have a structure of CV, VC, VV and are derived from the concept of "akara".
An akara describes a concept as something whole which can be broken down into two concepts which are understood as the opposites of each other by the speakers of the language. An akara is a word having structure of one of the following templates called "kinds".

Each Kind uses fixed set of vowels (akara kind : vowels):

First kind - C1VC1 (Consonant, vowel, same consonant) :  a, u;
Second kind - V1CV1 (Vowel, consonant, same vowel) : o, i;
Third kind - V1V2V1 (One vowel, second vowel, first vowel again): a,o,u,i.

Strategies:

C1VC1: Consonant, vowel, same consonant

Examples:
1. lal : Brightness contrast. (bright, light - la) + (dark, shadow - al)
2. nun : Temporal span. (beginning, start - nu) + (end, finish - un)
3. kak : Causation principle. (cause, reason) - ka + (effect, result - ak)
4. mum : Vertical direction.  (up, above - mu) + (down, below - um)
5. sas : Spatial limit. (in, inside - sa) + (out, outside - as).

V1CV1: Vowel, consonant, same vowel

Examples:
1. oko : Accessibility state. (open - ok) + (closed - ko)
2. iji : Thermal range. (hot - ij) + (cold - ji)
3. ivi : Velocity factor. (fast - iv) + (slow - vi)
4. oro : Affection polarity. (love - or) + (hate - ro)
5. ili : Moral quality. (good - il) + (bad - li).

V1V2V1: One vowel, second vowel, first vowel again
1. a'o'a : Diurnal cycle. (day - a'o) + (night - o'a)
2.  a'u'a : Vital opposition. (life - a'u) + (death - u'a)
3. a'i'a : Causal sequence. (beginning - a'i) + (end - i'a)

You can create new words following one of the strategies below:

First strategy : C1V + C2V -> C1C2V.
Examples: la + ka -> lka, nu + ru -> rnu, so + vo -> svo, mi + ni -> mni;

Second strategy: C1V + VC2 -> C1VC2.
Examples: la + ak -> lak, ro + on -> ron, su + uj -> suj, ki + iv -> kiv;

Third strategy: VC1 + C2V -> VC1C2V.
Examples: al + na -> alna, uj + vu -> ujvu, ok + ro -> okro, ij + si -> ijsi;

Fourth strategy: CV1 + CV2 -> CV1V2.
Examples: ka + ki -> ka'i, su + so -> su'o, ri + ra -> ri'a, jo + ja -> jo'a;

Fifth strategy: VC1 + VC2 ->  VC1C2.
Examples: ar + al -> arl, uj + us -> ujs, or + ok -> ork, in + im -> inm.

