Sure, here is a sample C# code to create an Admin page in ASP.NET:

```
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Web;
using System.Web.UI;
using System.Web.UI.WebControls;

namespace YourAppName
{
    public partial class AdminPage : System.Web.UI.Page
    {
        protected void Page_Load(object sender, EventArgs e)
        {
            // Check if the user is authenticated and has Admin role
            // Redirect to login page if not authenticated or not an admin
            if (!User.Identity.IsAuthenticated || !User.IsInRole("Admin"))
            {
                Response.Redirect("~/Login.aspx");
            }
        }

        protected void btnLogout_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
        {
            // Logout the user and redirect to the login page
            FormsAuthentication.SignOut();
            Response.Redirect("~/Login.aspx");
        }
    }
}
```

In this sample, we have created an AdminPage class inherited from `System.Web.UI.Page`. The `Page_Load` event is used to check if the user is authenticated and has Admin role. If the user is not authenticated or not an admin, then it is redirected to the login page. The `btnLogout_Click` event logs out the user and redirects to the login page.

To use this code in your ASP.NET application, you can create a new web form and name it as AdminPage.aspx. Then, add the above C# code in AdminPage.aspx.cs file.

You can customize the design and functionality of your admin page according to your requirements.

