If your image is too wide to fit within the page margins even when you set its width using a command like `\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{image-file-name}`, then you can use the `\resizebox` command from the `graphicx` package to scale the image down to a smaller size that will fit within the margins.

Here's an example of how to use this command to resize an image:

```
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \resizebox{\textwidth}{!}{\includegraphics{image-file-name}}
  \caption{A caption for your image.}
  \label{fig:my-figure}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```

The `\resizebox{\textwidth}{!}` command scales the image down proportionally to fit within the current line width (i.e., the text width of your document), while preserving its aspect ratio. Note that you should replace `image-file-name` with the filename of your image.

With this setup, the image will be scaled down to a size that fits within the page margins while retaining its aspect ratio. If you find that the image is still too large or too small, you can adjust the scaling factor passed to `\resizebox` until you find a suitable size.

I apologize for the confusion. It is possible that the `\resizebox` command is not working for your image because it has a very large aspect ratio or because it is not well-suited for scaling down.

In that case, you could try a different approach to fit the wide image to the page. One option is to use `\makebox[\textwidth]{\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{image-file-name}}`, which will center align the image within the page margins.

Here's an example:

```
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \makebox[\textwidth]{\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{image-file-name}}
  \caption{A caption for your image.}
  \label{fig:my-figure}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```

Note that `\makebox[\textwidth]{...}` creates a box of width `\textwidth` that centers its contents horizontally within the box. The `\includegraphics` command is used within this box, with the `width=\linewidth` option to ensure the image occupies the full width of the box.

This approach should fit the wide image within the page margins. If the image is still too large, you may need to adjust the width of the image or use a different approach, such as cropping the image or creating a multi-panel figure.

The "dimension too large" error occurs in LaTeX when a value exceeds the maximum allowable size. This typically happens when you're trying to include a very large image, where the combined width and height exceed certain limits.

One possible solution to the "dimension too large" error is to use an external image editor or tool to resize the image outside of LaTeX, reducing its dimensions or resolution so that it becomes small enough to fit within the limits.

Alternatively, you can use the `adjustbox` package to resize the image before including it in LaTeX. The `adjustbox` package provides the `\maxsizebox` command that scales an object down to fit within specified maximum dimensions.

Here's an example:

```
\usepackage{graphicx}
\usepackage{adjustbox}

\begin{document}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \maxsizebox{\textwidth}{!}{\includegraphics{image-file-name}}
  \caption{A caption for your image.}
  \label{fig:my-figure}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```

The `\maxsizebox{\textwidth}{!}{\includegraphics{image-file-name}}` command scales the image down to fit within the width of the page, while keeping its aspect ratio. Note that you should replace `image-file-name` with the filename of your image.

